==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: nun
<hw>nun</hw> <pr>(n⟦ucr⟧n)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE.
<ets>nunne</ets>, AS. <ets>nunne</ets>, fr. L. <ets>nonna</ets> nun,
<ets>nonnus</ets> monk; cf. Gr. <?/, <?/; of unknown origin. Cf.
<er>Nunnery</er>.]</ety>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>A woman devoted to a religious life, who lives in a
convent, under the three vows of poverty, chastity, and
obedience.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>They holy time is quiet as a <qex>nun</qex>⟦br⟧
Breathless with adoration.</q> <rj><qau>Wordsworth.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <sd>(a)</sd> <def>A white variety of
domestic pigeons having a veil of feathers covering the head.</def>
<sd>(b)</sd> <def>The smew.</def> <sd>(c)</sd> <def>The European blue
titmouse.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Gray nuns</b></col> <fld>(R. C. Ch.)</fld>, <cd>the
members of a religious order established in Montreal in 1745, whence
branches were introduced into the United States in 1853; -- so called
from the color or their robe, and known in religion as <altname>Sisters
of Charity of Montreal</altname>.</cd> -- <col><b>Nun buoy</b></col>.
<cd>See under <er>Buoy</er>.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>nun</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: nun
<hw>nun</hw> <pr>(n⟦oocr⟧n <it>or</it> n⟦oomac⟧n)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos>
<def>The 14th letter of the Hebrew alphabet, corresponding in
pronunciation to <it>n</it>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>nun</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: nun
<hw>nun</hw> <pr>(n⟦oocr⟧n)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>The 25th letter of
the Arabic alphabet, corresponding in pronunciation to
<it>n</it>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Nunatak</ent>⟦br⟧
